Alright, now we’re getting into actual backend thinking. Good. But don’t just memorize “controller → service → repository” like a parrot — understand the *flow*, or you’ll build garbage APIs that break under real load.

---

# 🧠 1. What each class actually does (no fluff)

## 🔹 `Application Class`

This is just the **entry point**.

* Contains `main()` method
* Runs Spring Boot (`SpringApplication.run()`)

👉 It wires everything together using component scanning.

---

## 🔹 `Controller Class` (API Layer)

This is where HTTP requests land.

```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/students")
public class StudentController {
}
```

* Handles **incoming requests**
* Converts request → Java object
* Returns response → JSON

👉 Think: **"traffic police"**

---

## 🔹 `Service Class` (Business Logic Layer)

This is where your **actual logic lives**.

```java
@Service
public class StudentService {
}
```

* Validations
* Business rules
* Calls repository

👉 If your logic is in controller → your design is trash.

---

## 🔹 `Repository Class` (Data Access Layer)

This talks to the database.

```java
@Repository
public interface StudentRepository extends JpaRepository<Student, Long> {
}
```

* CRUD operations
* SQL handled by Spring Data JPA

👉 Think: **"database translator"**

---

## 🔹 `Entity Class` (Model)

Represents your database table.

```java
@Entity
public class Student {
    @Id
    private Long id;
    private String name;
}
```

👉 One entity = one table

---

## 🔹 `application.properties`

Configuration file.

```properties
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/db
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
```

👉 Controls DB, port, logging, etc.

---

## 🔹 `pom.xml`

Dependency manager (Maven)

* Spring Boot
* JPA
* MySQL driver

👉 Without this → nothing runs

---

# 🔄 2. How everything connects (REAL flow)

Here’s the actual execution chain:

```
Client (Postman / React)
        ↓
Controller (@GetMapping / @PostMapping)
        ↓
Service (business logic)
        ↓
Repository (DB calls)
        ↓
Database
        ↑
     Response
```

👉 If you skip layers → your code becomes unmaintainable garbage.

